PlantTissue.Bark: Plant tissue outside the vascular cambium or the xylem; in older trees may be divided into dead outer bark and living inner bark, which consists of secondary phloem.
PlantTissue.Conduit: A water-transporting element in a plant.
PlantTissue.ConduitLumen: The cavity bounded by a conduit cell wall.
PlantTissue.LeafVascularBundle: A unit strand of the vascular system containing the vascular tissues, xylem and phloem in a leaf.

Phloem.comment: A portion of vascular tissue whose principal function is conducting organic substances.

PhloemCell.comment: A cell of the phloem, which is a part of vascular plant tissue whose principal function is conducting organic substances.

PlantTissue.comment: Formed by grouped differentiated plant cells.
PlantTissue.RootCambium: A lateral meristem, the cells of which divide mostly periclinally in the root.
PlantTissue.ShootCambium: A lateral meristem, the cells of which divide mostly periclinally in the shoot.

Wood.comment: A portion of xylem tissue that develops from a vascular cambium.
Wood.SapWood: Outer part of the wood of stem or root containing living cells in which conduction of water takes place.

Xylem.comment: A portion of vascular tissue composed of xylem elements.

XylemCell.comment: Plant cells that are part of the xylem and are often long tracheary elements that transport water.

Plant.Bark: Plant tissue outside the vascular cambium or the xylem; in older trees may be divided into dead outer bark and living inner bark, which consists of secondary phloem.
Plant.comment: Living organisms belonging to the kingdom Plantae that obtain most of their energy from sunlight via photosynthesis.
Plant.PlantResprout: Young plant growth, such as a bud or shoot.
Plant.PlantSeedling: A young plant that has grown from a seed.

RootSystem.comment: Plant axes that bear no leaves and are often found below ground.
RootSystem.CoarseRoot: Roots that have undergone secondary thickening and have a woody structure.
RootSystem.FineRoot: Primary roots, usually <2 mm in diameter, that are often heavily branched, support mycorrhizas and are short lived.
RootSystem.RootCambium: A lateral meristem, the cells of which divide mostly periclinally in the root.

Plant.Seed: A propagating organ formed in the reproductive cycle of gymnosperms and angiosperms, derived from the ovule and enclosing an embryo.

ShootSystem.comment: A collective plant structure that produces shoot apical meristems and the plant structures that arise from them.
ShootSystem.Canopy: The aboveground portion of a plant or plant community formed by plant crowns.
ShootSystem.Cotyledon: A leaf formed at the first node of a sporophyte.

Fruit.comment: A collective plant structure containing one or more embryos, which as a whole, develops from a gynoecium.
Fruit.Seed: A propagating organ formed in the reproductive cycle of gymnosperms and angiosperms, derived from the ovule and enclosing an embryo.

Inflorescence.comment: The part of the plant axial system that bears flowers and is typically above the uppermost foliage leaves.
Inflorescence.Flower: A reproductive shoot system that has at least one carpel or at least one stamen and does not contain any other determinate shoot system as a part.

ShootSystem.ShootCambium: A lateral meristem, the cells of which divide mostly periclinally in the shoot.

Stem.comment: A shoot axis that is the primary axis of a plant.

Branch.comment: A shoot axis that develops from an axillary meristem or from the shoot apical meristem.
Branch.Twig: A small thin terminal branch of a woody plant.

Leaf.comment: A phyllome that is not part of a flower.
Leaf.Cotyledon: A leaf formed at the first node of a sporophyte.
Leaf.LeafBlade: The lamina of a leaf, usually dorsiventrally flattened and expanded.
Leaf.LeafEpidermisCell: A leaf cell that constitutes leaf dermal tissue.
Leaf.LeafLaminaCell: A cell that is part of a leaf lamina.
Leaf.LeafMesophyllCell: A chlorenchyma cell that is part of a leaf mesophyll.
Leaf.LeafVascularBundle: A unit strand of the vascular system containing the vascular tissues, xylem and phloem in a leaf.
Leaf.Leaflet: A segment of a compound leaf.

PlantCell.comment: A cell of a plant, which typically has: a central vacuole; a cell wall composed of cellulose and hemicellulose; specialised cellâ€“cell pathways known as plasmodesmata; and plastids (like chloroplasts) that contain chlorophyll for photosynthesis.

SclerenchymaCell.comment: Sclerenchyma cells are the principal supporting cells in plant tissues that have ceased elongation, and whose walls consist of cellulose, hemicellulose and lignin.

XylemCell.comment: Plant cells that are part of the xylem and are often long tracheary elements that transport water.

Mitochondria.comment: A membrane-enclosed organelle that generates most of the cell's supply of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and  is involved in signaling, cellular differentiation, control of the cell cycle and cell growth.

Organelle.comment: A specialized subunit within a cell that has a specific function and is usually separately enclosed within its own lipid bilayer.
